label chapter4:

    # [Scene: The Green Spire Rooftop | Night]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fast, hopeful strings with driving percussion — urgent, forward-moving]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain on corrugated metal, the steady tap of boots on wet wood, distant horns muffled by weather]
    "You climb the ladder two at a time because there is too much to do and because staying still feels like sinking. The Spire exhales green light as you reach the deck; moss-filtered skylights throw soft pools where water beads and runs in miniature rivers."

    scene bg ch4_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The metallic rattle of measuring tape, the soft scuff of boots]
    show elliot_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "You're soaked. Thought you'd bail and leave me to wrestle the anchors."
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "I wouldn't make your prototype suffer alone."
    "You debate adding: 'Not tonight.' You don't. The rain makes blunt punctuation of everything."
    "He laughs — the sound bright against the rain — and holds out a pair of gloves you know are his size but that somehow fit your hands anyway. There is a moment where you catch"
    "the vial of dune grass seeds at his throat chiming against a leather cord; it seems to pulse with the same cadence as the tide."
    "The work is kinetic and fast. You measure anchor depths with a borrowed sonic gauge, Elliot reads the wave data on his patched smartwatch, and together you debate how deep the braided root-mesh must sink before"
    "the next swell. The argument is practical — torque versus give, soil retention versus weight — but there is a cordial sparring to it, an exchange that keeps the night sharp and lit."

    elliot_chen "If we go too shallow, the pilings will pivot like a seesaw. Too deep and we blow half the budget on excavation. Compromise at two meters, staggered anchors, and use the reed mat as sacrificial friction."

    maya_rios "Two meters makes sense on flat substrate, not on the reclaimed slat. The pilings there are soft; we'd need longer helix anchors or a spread foundation."
    "You tap the digital plan. You don't say how your chest tightens when the word 'budget' hovers; you don't have to. He reads it in the pause."

    elliot_chen "Spread foundation. Okay."
    "He looks at you, then at the panel, then back at you. 'We can scavenge half the helix mounts from the derelict dock. Sami can drive the boat.'"

    maya_rios "Sami will be here."
    "You almost add: 'Because you said so.' Instead, you settle to the task. Saying it aloud would make it more true."
    "You braid root-mesh with hands that know the language of repairs — the sore knuckles, the patient rhythm. The tendrils of reed and vine resist at first, stubborn as a child's refusal, and then give. You"
    "laugh when a vine wraps around your wrist and refuses to be free, and Elliot mirrors you with a look that softens the edges at your mouth."

    menu:
        "Tease Elliot about wearing the seed vial like a necklace":
            "You elbow him, joking that his vial is the spire's lucky charm. He grins and tucks it closer to his heart, calling it 'professional superstition.' The moment loosens something—more laughter, more ease in the shoulders."
        "Focus on the math and call out the precise anchor spacing":
            "You point to the schematic and call out numbers. Elliot falters only a beat before matching your cadence. The exchange becomes a duet of competence; electricity hums in the shared attention."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "Rain slices the night into quick, bright beats; the surf is a percussion line beneath the city. Sami arrives like a warm wind: neon lifevest, wet braid slung over one shoulder, thermoses steaming in a battered"
    "messenger bag. They drop the thermoses at your feet as if they're offering the Spire a small, private altar."
    show sami_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    sami_alvarez "List of volunteers."
    "They hand you a waterlogged sheet folded into neat segments. 'Kayak teams, a rigging crew, three neighbors who've got old pilings to spare. Also—' They look between you and Elliot '—two hands that can do fine filigree carpentry, if we need to finesse the glass insets.'"

    maya_rios "Good."
    "You take the list with fingers that leave prints in the damp ink. 'We need every salvage team we can get. If this holds through low tide tests, it's proof for the council and for people who still don't believe in living systems.'"

    sami_alvarez "And if it doesn't hold?"
    "Their voice is practical, but even practical is edged tonight."

    maya_rios "Then we rebuild and we learn. We don't hand the shoreline to concrete until we've exhausted scaleable options."
    "You say the thing you've been training yourself to say in council and on benches: 'we learn.' Saying it aloud pulls at the rough, old scar under your ribs — the one you keep for your brother. You steady it away with work."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive strings accelerate — urgency rising]
    hide elliot_chen
    hide maya_rios
    hide sami_alvarez

    scene bg ch4_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The splash of test water, your breath, Sami's muttered tool checks]
    "You run the first test. Reed panels stand on their frames, reclaimed glass inset like a lattice, irrigation lines pinned to the backbone by Elliot's quick clamps. You pump freshwater into the basin; the design drinks,"
    "swells, and then—there is a small, impossible moment where the water sits like a held note. The structure flexes and doesn't fail. The sound you all make is something between a laugh and a small, relieved"
    "exhalation."
    show elliot_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "It sings."
    "Your hands on the piling, feeling tension where slack used to be."
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "It holds."
    "You feel the word not as assurance but as a promise that has to be kept. For a second, all the bureaucracy, the hearings, Irene's sharp smile, the word 'budget' — they become materials to be shaped rather than insurmountable walls."
    "You and Elliot test tension on a salvaged piling. You brace the line; he counts in half-breaths and you pull in sync. The rope hums, the helix bites, and then gives a whispering, stubborn hold. The prototype flexes and absorbs the motion like a living thing."

    elliot_chen "Okay—"
    "He wipes mud from his hands on his smock, paint-stain darkening the cuff. '—we can scale this. With staggered panels, integrated irrigation, and seed mixes for dune retention, we get three levels of resilience. We present that to the council as a pilot—'"

    maya_rios "—and we need demonstration data before the hearing."
    "You are already calculating the runs, the tidal windows, the volunteer shifts. Your pulse is a metronome of logistics now: short, fast, insistently forward."

    elliot_chen "Right. Two-week runs during low tide windows, sensor loads, sampler arrays. Sami can coordinate volunteers. Dr. Noor can vouch for the data. We can make the math sing like you did tonight."
    "You feel heat at that phrase, a small, private ember. You deflect it with the only tool you know in this room."

    maya_rios "We're going to need a permit for pilings."

    elliot_chen "Legal paperwork is romance language for 'we will fill out forms for the future.' Besides—"
    "He steps closer under the canopy of moss and bulbs; proximity feels like a small, dangerous current. '—I don't want to do this with anyone who doesn't believe it can work. Will you—' He clears his"
    "throat, voice dropping to something both small and enormous '—will you co-lead the pilot with me?'"
    "Your whole body rearranges to hear the question. The deck seems to tilt; the rain is no longer background but a crowd of whispered witnesses. The words are technical — 'co-lead' — but they are threaded"
    "with personal weight. It is an invitation to share responsibility and a request to share burden. The two are not the same, but in your chest they become interchangeable."
    hide elliot_chen
    hide maya_rios

    scene bg ch4_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The rain hushes to a single, expectant fall; the building creaks softly, as if holding its breath]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings soar to a peak — urgent, hopeful, trembling]
    "You taste fear — an old, familiar salt — rising at the back of your throat. To say yes is to accept a different kind of dependence, to let someone else hold a piece of what"
    "you've kept rigid and private. To say no is to keep carrying alone and risk the brittle fracture that comes at the last storm."
    "You study his hands. They are paint-stained, knuckled with small scars of building, and steady the way hands are when they have learned to shape things from chaos. You remember the way your brother's small hand"
    "trusted you once, the way you learned, very early, that trust could be life-saving. The memory is both map and minefield."
    show elliot_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "I know it's a lot."
    "He rushes, then halts, the comedic timing of someone used to softening hard facts. 'This is technical, yes. Political, yes. And—' He searches your face '—personal. I want you in the room with me when we"
    "present. I want your name next to mine on the permit. I want your judgment when things go sideways.'"
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "You want me to share the load, all of it?"
    "The question is small but true."

    elliot_chen "Not all at once. Not without boundaries. But with you, yes. With you I think we can stop rebuilding in panic and start building with memory."
    "He offers you that thought like a tool, tangible as a clamp."
    "Sami watches from the edge of the workbench, arms crossed, mouth corners lifted in the half-smile of someone who already knows what it costs to ask and what it costs not to. They clap once, loud enough to break the hush."
    show sami_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    sami_alvarez "Decision time's not supposed to be dramatic, Mayita. But hey—"
    "They nod toward the harbor. '—if it helps, the neighbors already think you're the captain. Might be nice to have the co-captain badge.'"
    "You laugh, sharp and incredulous, because the tell-tale hum in your ribs is not entirely fear; there is an ember of something like relief."

    maya_rios "Captain and co-captain. I hate maritime metaphors."
    "You say it, and mean it, but your shoulders loosen."

    menu:
        "Ask Elliot to sketch out how responsibilities will be divided":
            "You pull the wet schematic closer and ask for specifics—who handles procurement, who does volunteer rotation, who signs the permits. Elliot begins listing, precise and open; the night turns bureaucratic in a good way, a plan forming in shared sentences."
        "Answer with a personal question instead — ask why he wants you specifically":
            "You ask him, quietly: 'Why me?' Elliot falters, then talks about trust, competence, and how your presence changes the room's gravity. The answer is not a guarantee, but it lands like sunlight through a gap in cloud."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "Your breath is a fast, bright thread. The Spire feels suddenly apocryphal and sacred, a place where things can be retaught. You can already hear the council chamber and Irene Voss's polished sentences, the ledger of"
    "compromises she likes to count on. But right now the only ledger you care to balance is the one of breaths shared between two people building a thing."
    "Elliot Chen steps forward, hand extended — not for a shake, but as a real, unadorned offer."

    elliot_chen "I want you with me, Maya. As co-lead. As partner on the pilot. We can be careful—smart—about what we promise. But I need you there."
    "You stand at the edge of a decision that feels like the hinge of the season. Saying yes will alter the shape of everything: your obligations, your identity, the way you once bore everything alone."
    hide elliot_chen
    hide maya_rios
    hide sami_alvarez

    scene bg ch4_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Crescendo to the chapter's emotional peak — urgent, breathless, hopeful]
    "You open your mouth."
    # [Page-Turn: The air tastes of salt and hot metal; the invitation hangs between you like a lit fuse of possibility. The next breath will decide partnership and plan, the personal and the political braided into one action.]

